				\begin{document}$$p \times h\nu = N \times E_{\mathrm{x}}$$\end{document}where p is the number of photons involved in the MPE, N is the number of excitons created through MEG and Ex is the energy of a single exciton. In order to confirm this theory, we look at MPE at excitation wavelengths away from the observed resonances and focus on the order of the excitation process (Fig. 3c). The PL intensity drops off steeply for excitation wavelengths longer than 1030 nm, corresponding to twice the band-gap energy of the CsPbBr3 NCs. For slightly shorter wavelengths, the PL intensity scales proportionally to (Iexc)2, while for slightly longer wavelengths the PL intensity clearly scales with (Iexc)3 (Supplementary Fig. 5). These values confirm that the drop off region marks the onset of two-photon absorption (2PA), while PL emission for excitation at longer wavelengths requires three photon absorption (3PA). For shorter wavelengths the order of the absorption process remains around 2 or slightly below this value (see Supplementary Fig. 6). Close to the resonance at λ3 the order jumps up to a value of 3 again, and at λ4, the order increases to 4. In between these resonances, the order decreases rapidly to 2. This suggests that the specific resonances are indeed necessary to promote the higher order MPE. Notably, the PL decreases abruptly to almost zero for excitation wavelengths shorter than 680 nm. At these wavelengths, four photon absorption leads to energies in excess of 7 eV, which could possibly induce ionization of the NCs, opening a new non-radiative decay channel.
